<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-477-094  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 477 094.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 18 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japanese seek Malaysian investment.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Worsley, Michael; Roowi, S.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Malaysia. Industrial Development AuthorityInvestmentsJapan External Trade OrganizationJapanForeign InvestmentGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JAPANESE SEEK MALAYSIAN INVESTMENT KUALA LUMPUR, MALAYSIA, 1989 JUL 11 (NB)-- Ten small and medium- sized Japanese companies want to invest in Malaysiaand will apply to the Malaysian Industrial Development Authority (Mida) forlicences to do so once their feasibility studies are completed, according toa Japanese government official yesterday.andP;  The areas they hope to invest ininclude the manufacture of  ceramics, floppy disks, furniture, magnetic headsand resin for integrated circuits and plastics, according to Hiroshi Ozawa,managing director of the Japan External Trade Organization centre here.andO;Ozawa said that they had applied to participate in the Jetro OverseasInvestment Scheme (Join Scheme) at Jetro's headquarters in Tokyo.andP;  Launchedin October 1986 to support the industrialization of Asian countries by theorganization of direct investment and transfer of technology from Japan, thescheme is aimed at giving assistance to small and medium-scale industries.andO;As of last month, 13 out of 24 approved Join Scheme projects have begunoperations here.andP;  Investors of the Join Scheme are unique in that theypossess brand originality in Japan or the U.S.andP;  (Michael Worsley andamp;S.Roowi/19890711)</TEXT></DOC>